At the time of this forecast, Cook, Inside Elections, Sabato, 538, PredictIt, Kalshi, and the Good Judgment Open crowd forecast are unanimous in favor of the Democratic party candidate to win the US Senate seat in CO. Given that level of agreement, I would consider this a major, major upset if it went the other way.
This could be an upset victory for the GOP; however, Colorado is solidly blue.
Pretty consistent lead for Bennet and it’s holding steady.

Biden won Colorado by 13.5 points in 2020. It is a point bluer than South Carolina is red. In 2016, Michael Bennet won his race by 5.6, outdoing Hillary in the state by almost 2 points. Barring some really huge gaffes on Senator Bennet's part, here really aren't many realistic paths for Republicans to win this.

Educated guess based on

Incumbent Senator Michael Bennet is extremely likely to win reelection. Current projections from Nate Silver’s 538 and race to the White House predict that Bennet has a 91% (https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/2022-election-forecast/senate/) and 95.4% ( https://www.racetothewh.com/senate/colorado) chance of reelection as of August 2022. While Bennet may be facing a galvanized moderate Republican candidate in what will likely be a tough election cycle for Democrats, he previously eked out at slim victory in the disastrous (for Democrats) 2010 midterm elections. Democrats have also won 4 out of the last 5 Senate races in Colorado and the state has gone for a Democratic candidate in every Presidential election since 2008 (https://www.270towin.com/states/Colorado). Given Colorado’s move toward the left and his previous electoral successes, I put Bennet’s probability of reelection at 90%.

Adjusting towards crowd, but still wondering whether or not the crowd can be justified in being THAT confident (1 in 100 chance of being wrong is pretty confident!)…big electoral surprises aren’t that rare these days.

“The GOP brand is still tarnished in Colorado,” said Alan Salazar, chief of staff to Denver’s Democratic mayor, Michael Hancock. “O’Dea needs to overcome that by making a clean break from Trump.” That, however, risks alienating Republicans, requiring O’Dea to walk a fine line. As a political novice, it’s not clear he has the skill to do that.

Adjusting down

PredictIt has it at much higher odds for the Democratic Party candidate. But I am in skeptic mode because @MrLittleTexas says, "Bennet has never won with more than 50% of the vote, and the GOP candidate is a moderate pro choice businessman without any Trump or Jan 6 baggage." In addition, polls across the country has seen an increase in confidence of the Republican Party to handle key issues while confidence in the Democratic Party has gone down. The Senate elections as a whole is more uncertain than the House elections. But I remain on the Democratic bias because my forecast for the US Senate winning a majority leans more toward the Democratic Party.
